mily:Arial; font-size:12pt">East Kent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has experienced accelerated growth as a result of high speed services on both HS1 and the classic lines.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o maximise these benefits, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we established </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the HS2 Growth Task Force </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to leave </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">no stone unturned in pursuit of growth </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> HS2. The task force is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">led by Lord </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Deighton</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s members from business, loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">al government and academia.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 4: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Will HS2 be value for money?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HS2 Ltd has reviewed all the key elements of the economic case for HS2. This includes using updated demand figures and values of time, as well as incorporating the latest assessment of the costs of HS2, as set out in the Government’s Spending Round announc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ement in June 2013. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The analysis found that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he full Y network will deliver ‘high’ value for money </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with a benefit-cost ratio of 2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is similar to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crossrail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and higher than the benefit-cost ratio for some other major projects when approved, such as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hameslink</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the Jubilee Line extension.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Phase One on its own</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BCR of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.7</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, which is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">‘medium’ value for money</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HS2 Ltd has undertaken extensive analysis to understand the robustness of the benefit-cost ratio to changes in the assumptions made, includi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng on economic growth, demand growth and costs. These demonstrate that our benefit-cost ratio is extremely robust and that even if a raft of downside risks materialised, the full Y network will still deliver ‘medium’ value for money. We will continue to ke</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ep our assessment under review as the scheme progresses to take account of new information to ensure it continues to reflect both upside and downside risks.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> standard </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assessment model assumes that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">demand </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stops at a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pre-determined level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the future. For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HS2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this level is reached</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2036, only three years after Phase Two open</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have modelled what would happen i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f demand continued to rise to 2049</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under this scenario, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">British people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">still travelling less by</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">than people in Spa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">do now, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the benefit-cost ratio would rise to 4.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> ‘very high’ value for money. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 5: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is HS2 affordable</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and how will costs be kept under control</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HM Treasury, through the 2013 Spending Round settlement, set a clear funding envelope within</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which HS2 will be delivered. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he funding envelope includes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£21.4bn for Phase One, £21.2bn for Phase Two and £7.5bn for rolling stock (all in 2011 prices, excluding VAT). </span><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="425" height="157" alt="" /></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Managing costs is at the heart of everything we do</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ithin the cost</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> envelope</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S2 Ltd has been set a demanding target price for construction of Phase One of £17.16bn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authority to manage co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sts up to £19.4bn but</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ccess to funding over </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this level</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> requires the approval of HM Treasury and would involve penalty payment by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DfT.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Phase One costs have been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">independently</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assur</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and cross-check</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Phase Two cost estimates and the associated design are at an earlier stage</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and so have a higher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> level of contingency.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sir David Higgins has been appointed as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is the new Chairman of HS2 Ltd and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has a brief to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> keep costs down</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HS2 will deliver significant increases in land value and excellent development and regeneration opportunities. We expect to work with the private sector to take advantage of this and reduce the overall cost to the public purse. We are also carefully consid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ering the future operating model for the railway and the potential to realise revenue benefits from it as a valuable part of national infrastructure. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Verdana; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Question 6:  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What does the recent report by KPMG tell us?</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In April 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HS2 Ltd commissioned KPMG to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">produce a report on the regional economic impacts of HS2, with a particular focus on the city regions connected by the proposed HS2 network.  The aim of this work was to understand the potential productivity gains from the investment in HS2, and how the sc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">heme might change the future distribution of economic output across the country.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The issue of how HS2 could support regional economic growth is important, but analysis of these potential effects is incredibly complex and is not something that is captured w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ithin the current economic appraisal of HS2. The KPMG report is the first attempt to quantify these potential impacts and, as with any analysis of this nature, it relies upon a number of assumptions and results are subject to uncertainty.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The approach take</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n in the KPMG report is to measure the impact that investment in HS2 will have on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> connectivity, and to estimate how this improved connectivity might deliver productivity gains and a change in the distribution of economic output.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This approach is bas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed on sound economic theory, and was reviewed by a panel of independent experts set up by HS2 Ltd.  This panel provided advice on the proposed methodology and results, which KPMG considered in finalising the report.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The initial report was published in Sept</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ember 2013, and this confirms that investment in HS2 will deliver widespread connectivity improvements.  Connectivity improves on and off the network, which reflects access to new high speed services and benefits of released capacity on the classic network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  There are connectivity benefits in terms of business-to-business connectivity (the number of businesses within reach of any one area) and labour connectivity (the effective supply of labour to any one area).  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On the basis that increases in connectivity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> increases effective business and labour markets, and thus increase opportunities to trade, the KPMG analysis </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">shows that the connectivity improvements associated with HS2 could support growth in key city regions, by effectively making them more competitive</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The headline figure for the estimated annual boost to the British economy is £15bn (measured in 2037, in 2013 prices).  Analysis of location effects suggest that all regions are estimated to benefit from HS2, with the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Midlands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the North doing parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cularly well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he methodological approach, data sources, and assumptions made in the analysis is clearly documented within the KPMG report.  In recognition of the limitations in carrying out this type of analysis, the report also includes a sensitivity tes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t which shows that with more cautious estimates in relation to the importance of connectivity, the estimated annual impact reduces to £8bn.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">These results provide a useful first step in understanding the potential for HS2 to boost economic growth by improvi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng connectivity and how the scheme could change the future distribution of economic output.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We recognise that forecasting these effects is challenging, and results are uncertain, but it is important to develop the evidence in this area given the transforma</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tional nature of the project.  HS2 Ltd will continue to refine the methodological approach and explore alternatives in order to strengthen the evidence in this area.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is important to note that these initial results are not directly comparable to the econ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">omic appraisal.  The KPMG analysis is separate from the cost benefit analysis, and given the difference in approach, results are not directly comparable (or additional) to the benefit cost ratio.  This work should be considered as part of the wider evidenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e base as a complement to the appraisal, which provides useful information on the potential for HS2 to boost economic growth, particularly in key city regions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 7.7pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>